<h2>‚úÖ Distraction Technique</h2>

You quickly walk up and "accidentally" bump into them, spilling your drink slightly.

<strong>You say:</strong> "Oh my god, I'm so sorry! Are you okay? Let me get you some napkins..."

This creates enough disruption that the intoxicated person sits down on the stairs, and you're able to stay with them while the other person walks away looking frustrated.

<div class="feedback-box">
<h3>üí™ Why This Worked:</h3>

<strong>‚úì Indirect interruption:</strong> Broke up the situation without direct confrontation

<strong>‚úì Created physical barrier:</strong> You positioned yourself between them

<strong>‚úì Gave time:</strong> Allowed the intoxicated person to reconsider

<strong>‚úì Low-risk approach:</strong> If you misjudged the situation, it's just an accident

<h4>Other Distraction Techniques:</h4>
- Fake phone call: "Your roommate needs you"
- Ask for help: "Can you help me find my friend?"
- Pretend you know them: "Oh hey! I didn't know you were here!"
- Create commotion: Knock something over, start a game

<h4>Remember:</h4>
Distraction is great when you're uncomfortable with direct confrontation or want to minimize conflict.
</div>

<strong>Skill Earned:</strong> Distraction Techniques ‚≠ê

